\par
TypeScript Config\par
Payload exposes a variety of TypeScript settings that you can leverage. These settings are used to auto-generate TypeScript interfaces for your Collections and Globals, and to ensure that Payload uses your Generated Types for all Local API methods.\par
\par
To customize the TypeScript settings, use the typescript property in your Payload Config:\par
\par
import \{ buildConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export default buildConfig(\{\par
  // ...\par
  typescript: \{\par
    // ...\par
  \},\par
\})\par
The following options are available:\par
\par
Option\par
\par
Description\par
\par
autoGenerate\par
\par
By default, Payload will auto-generate TypeScript interfaces for all collections and globals that your config defines. Opt out by setting typescript.autoGenerate: false. More details.\par
\par
declare\par
\par
By default, Payload adds a declare block to your generated types, which makes sure that Payload uses your generated types for all Local API methods. Opt out by setting typescript.declare: false.\par
\par
outputFile\par
\par
Control the output path and filename of Payload's auto-generated types by defining the typescript.outputFile property to a full, absolute path.\par
\par
strictDraftTypes\par
\par
Enable strict type safety for draft mode. When enabled: (1) Query operations (find, findByID) with draft: true will type required fields as optional, since validation is skipped for drafts. (2) The draft property is forbidden for collections without drafts in create operations. (3) Create operations enforce proper data requirements via discriminated unions. Defaults to false. This will become the default behavior in v4.0.\par
\par
Config Location\par
For Payload command-line scripts, we need to be able to locate your Payload Config. We'll check a variety of locations for the presence of payload.config.ts by default, including:\par
\par
The root current working directory\par
The compilerOptions in your `tsconfig`*\par
The dist directory*\par
* Config location detection is different between development and production environments. See below for more details.\par
\par
Important: Ensure your tsconfig.json is properly configured for Payload to auto-detect your config location. If it does not exist, or does not specify the proper compilerOptions, Payload will default to the current working directory.\par
\par
Development Mode\par
\par
In development mode, if the configuration file is not found at the root, Payload will attempt to read your tsconfig.json, and attempt to find the config file specified in the rootDir:\par
\par
\{\par
  // ...\par
  "compilerOptions": \{\par
    "rootDir": "src"\par
  \}\par
\}\par
Production Mode\par
\par
In production mode, Payload will first attempt to find the config file in the outDir of your tsconfig.json, and if not found, will fallback to the rootDir directory:\par
\par
\{\par
  // ...\par
  "compilerOptions": \{\par
    "outDir": "dist",\par
    "rootDir": "src"\par
  \}\par
\}\par
If none was in either location, Payload will finally check the dist directory.\par
\par
Customizing the Config Location\par
In addition to the above automated detection, you can specify your own location for the Payload Config. This can be useful in situations where your config is not in a standard location, or you wish to switch between multiple configurations. To do this, Payload exposes an Environment Variable to bypass all automatic config detection.\par
\par
To use a custom config location, set the PAYLOAD_CONFIG_PATH environment variable:\par
\par
\{\par
  "scripts": \{\par
    "payload": "PAYLOAD_CONFIG_PATH=/path/to/custom-config.ts payload"\par
  \}\par
\}\par
Tip: PAYLOAD_CONFIG_PATH can be either an absolute path, or path relative to your current working directory.\par
\par
Telemetry\par
Payload collects completely anonymous telemetry data about general usage. This data is super important to us and helps us accurately understand how we're growing and what we can do to build the software into everything that it can possibly be. The telemetry that we collect also help us demonstrate our growth in an accurate manner, which helps us as we seek investment to build and scale our team. If we can accurately demonstrate our growth, we can more effectively continue to support Payload as free and open-source software. To opt out of telemetry, you can pass telemetry: false within your Payload Config.\par
\par
For more information about what we track, take a look at our privacy policy.\par
\par
Cross-origin resource sharing (CORS)\par
Cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) can be configured with either a whitelist array of URLS to allow CORS requests from, a wildcard string (*) to accept incoming requests from any domain, or an object with the following properties:\par
\par
Option\par
\par
Description\par
\par
origins\par
\par
Either a whitelist array of URLS to allow CORS requests from, or a wildcard string ('*') to accept incoming requests from any domain.\par
\par
headers\par
\par
A list of allowed headers that will be appended in Access-Control-Allow-Headers.\par
\par
Here's an example showing how to allow incoming requests from any domain:\par
\par
import \{ buildConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export default buildConfig(\{\par
  // ...\par
  cors: '*',\par
\})\par
Here's an example showing how to append a new header (x-custom-header) in Access-Control-Allow-Headers:\par
\par
import \{ buildConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export default buildConfig(\{\par
  // ...\par
  cors: \{\par
    origins: ['{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://localhost:3000 }}{\fldrslt{http://localhost:3000\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22 '],\par
    headers: ['x-custom-header'],\par
  \},\par
\})\par
TypeScript\par
You can import types from Payload to help make writing your config easier and type-safe. There are two main types that represent the Payload Config, Config and SanitizedConfig.\par
\par
The Config type represents a raw Payload Config in its full form. Only the bare minimum properties are marked as required. The SanitizedConfig type represents a Payload Config after it has been fully sanitized. Generally, this is only used internally by Payload.\par
\par
import type \{ Config, SanitizedConfig \} from 'payload'\par
Server vs. Client\par
The Payload Config only lives on the server and is not allowed to contain any client-side code. That way, you can load up the Payload Config in any server environment or standalone script, without having to use Bundlers or Node.js loaders to handle importing client-only modules (e.g. scss files or React Components) without any errors.\par
\par
Behind the curtains, the Next.js-based Admin Panel generates a ClientConfig, which strips away any server-only code and enriches the config with React Components.\par
\par
Compatibility flags\par
The Payload Config can accept compatibility flags for running the newest versions but with older databases. You should only use these flags if you need to, and should confirm that you need to prior to enabling these flags.\par
\par
allowLocalizedWithinLocalized\par
\par
Payload localization works on a field-by-field basis. As you can nest fields within other fields, you could potentially nest a localized field within a localized field\f1\emdash but this would be redundant and unnecessary. There would be no reason to define a localized field within a localized parent field, given that the entire data structure from the parent field onward would be localized.\par
\par
By default, Payload will remove the localized: true property from sub-fields if a parent field is localized. Set this compatibility flag to true only if you have an existing Payload MongoDB database from pre-3.0, and you have nested localized fields that you would like to maintain without migrating.\par
\par
Logger\par
Payload uses Pino as its logger. By default, Payload logs pretty-printed output to stdout. You can customise this through the logger option in your config.\par
\par
The logger option accepts one of three forms:\par
\par
1. Logger options with an optional destination stream\par
Pass a \{ options, destination? \} object to configure the logger. options accepts standard Pino logger options such as level and name. An optional destination stream can be supplied as a second argument.\par
\par
import \{ buildConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export default buildConfig(\{\par
  logger: \{\par
    options: \{\par
      level: 'debug',\par
    \},\par
  \},\par
\})\par
To write logs to a file, pass a destination stream:\par
\par
import \{ buildConfig \} from 'payload'\par
import \{ pino \} from 'pino'\par
\par
export default buildConfig(\{\par
  logger: \{\par
    options: \{ level: 'info' \},\par
    destination: pino.destination('/var/log/payload.log'),\par
  \},\par
\})\par
Compatibility note: The transport property of Pino's LoggerOptions may fail with "unable to determine transport target" in some environments. Pino transports spawn a worker thread with their own module resolution, which can break when modules are bundled or the project uses ESM. If you encounter this error, use a pre-instantiated logger instead (see below).\par
\par
2. Pre-instantiated logger\par
Pass a fully configured Pino logger instance. This is the recommended approach when you need custom transports, formatters, or pino-pretty in development:\par
\par
import \{ buildConfig \} from 'payload'\par
import \{ pino \} from 'pino'\par
import pinoPretty from 'pino-pretty'\par
\par
const logger = pino(\{ level: 'debug' \}, pinoPretty(\{ colorize: true \}))\par
\par
export default buildConfig(\{\par
  logger,\par
\})\par
3. Disabling logging\par
Set the DISABLE_LOGGING environment variable to 'true' to suppress all log output:\par
\par
DISABLE_LOGGING=true node server.js\par
Custom bin scripts\par
Using the bin configuration property, you can inject your own scripts to npx payload. Example for pnpm payload seed:\par
\par
Step 1: create seed.ts file in the same folder with payload.config.ts with:\par
\par
import type \{ SanitizedConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
import payload from 'payload'\par
\par
// Script must define a "script" function export that accepts the sanitized config\par
export const script = async (config: SanitizedConfig) => \{\par
  await payload.init(\{ config \})\par
  await payload.create(\{\par
    collection: 'pages',\par
    data: \{ title: 'my title' \},\par
  \})\par
  payload.logger.info('Successfully seeded!')\par
  process.exit(0)\par
\}\par
Step 2: add the seed script to bin:\par
\par
export default buildConfig(\{\par
  bin: [\par
    \{\par
      scriptPath: path.resolve(dirname, 'seed.ts'),\par
      key: 'seed',\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\})\par
Now you can run the command using:\par
\par
pnpm payload seed\par
Running bin scripts on a schedule\par
Every bin script supports being run on a schedule using cron syntax. Simply pass the --cron flag followed by the cron expression when running the script. Example:\par
\par
pnpm payload run ./myScript.ts --cron "0 * * * *"\par
This will use the run bin script to execute the specified script on the defined schedule.\f0\par
}
